        <section xml:id="Section_4_1and2">
        <title>Section 4.1 and 4.2</title>
<subsection xml:id="Section_4_1and2_overview">
    <title> Overview</title>
    <p>
        Section 4.1 provides a brief biography of Gauss. These sections are interesting; you should read them.
    </p>
    <p>
        Section 4.2 introduces congruences and modular arithmetic.  Among other things this concept simplifies many of the results we've proved using the division algorithm. In particular it focuses on the remainders.  If you go back and look at the things we've proved using the division algorithm, it was always the remainder that was the important part.
    </p>
</subsection>

 <subsection xml:id="Question4_2_1">
    <title> Problem 1</title>
    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
            <p>
                Since <m>a \equiv b \pmod{n}</m>, <m>n|(a-b)</m>.  If <m>m|n</m>, then <m>m|(a-b)</m> so <m>a \equiv b \pmod{m}</m>.
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>n|a-b</m>, then <m>nk=a-b</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.   Mutliply by <m>c</m>:
                <md>
                    cnk=c(a-b)=ca-cb
                </md>
                and notice that <m>cn|ca-cb</m> which gives the desired congruence.
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                We have <m>nk=a-b</m> and, since <m>a,b,n</m> are all divisible by <m>d</m> we also have 
                <md>
                   \frac{n}{d}k=\frac{a}{d}-\frac{b}{d} 
                </md>
                which gives the desired congruence.
                
             
        
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
 </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="Question4_2_2">
    <title> Problem 1</title>
<p>
    <md>
        8^2 \equiv 2^2 \pmod{4}
    </md>
    but 
    <md>
        8 \not \equiv 2 \pmod{4}.
    </md>

    To build an example, pick <m>a,b,n</m> such that <m>n|(a-b)(a+b)</m> but <m>n \nmid a-b.</m> An easy way to do this is to distribute the prime factors of <m>n</m> between <m>a-b</m> and <m>a+b</m> such that neither contains all the prime factors of <m>n.</m>
</p>
  </subsection>
